I do agree that &lt;forms&gt; fundamentally serve the role of fulfilling HATEOAS.
However, I disagree that they are &quot;simply links with UI attached.&quot;  I&#39;d put
it a bit differently.  Forms define the exact nature of client interaction.
Note that &quot;Client&quot; doesn&#39;t necessarily mean UI; it can also mean
programmatic client.  Forms can be used to create hackable GET
URL?&lt;queryParam&gt;=&lt;value&gt;, but that&#39;s not the default behavior of &lt;forms&gt;;
The default is a POST.

Forms, IMHO, are severely underused in RESTful service environments.  The
concept of a server provided request template is a potentially powerful
mechanism of providing runtime meta-data about conversation semantics.  In
other words, forms can provide the same function as WSDL or WADL.  The
difference between forms and the W*DLs is that forms are generated to define
the semantics of complex interaction specifically related to the current
application state&#39;s workspace needs (meaning the accessible application
states that are most likely to be traversed by the client) rather than a
definite of an complete system definition.  WSDL/WADL define the details of
all application states, and forms define applicable details of applicable
application states.

-Solomon

